where C is the set of labels, âŠ• is the XOR operator between two binary variables, Pr(ğ‘“ (s âŠ• ğœ–) = ğ‘) is the probability that the base classifier ğ‘“ predicts label ğ‘ when we add random noise ğœ– to the structure vector s, and ğ‘”(s) is the label predicted for s by the smoothed classifier. Moreover, we note that ğ‘”(s âŠ• ğ›¿) is the label predicted for the perturbed structure vector s âŠ• ğ›¿. Existing randomized smoothing methods [5, 9, 21, 28, 32, 33] add random continuous noise (e.g.,
Gaussian noise, Laplacian noise) to a testing example (i.e., the structure vector s in our case). However, such continuous noise is not meaningful for the binary structure vector.
Our goal is to show that a label is provably the predicted label by the smoothed classifier ğ‘” for the perturbed structure vector s âŠ• ğ›¿ when the â„“0-norm of the adversarial perturbation ğ›¿, i.e., âˆ¥ğ›¿ âˆ¥0, is bounded. Next, we theoretically derive the certified perturbation
size ğ¾, prove the tightness of the certified perturbation size, and
discuss how to compute the certified perturbation size in practice.

3.2 Theoretical Certification
3.2.1 Overview. Let ğ‘‹ = s âŠ• ğœ– and ğ‘Œ = s âŠ• ğ›¿ âŠ• ğœ– be two random variables, where ğœ– is the random binary noise drawn from the distribution defined in Equation 1. ğ‘‹ and ğ‘Œ represent random structure vectors obtained by adding random binary noise ğœ– to the structure vector s and its perturbed version s âŠ• ğ›¿, respectively.
Suppose, when taking ğ‘‹ as an input, the base GNN classifier ğ‘“ correctly predicts the label ğ‘ğ´ with the largest probability. Then, our key idea is to guarantee that, when taking ğ‘Œ as an input, ğ‘“ still predicts ğ‘ğ´ with the largest probability. Moreover, we denote ğ‘ğµ as the predicted label by ğ‘“ with the second largest probability.
Then, our goal is to find the maximum perturbation size such that the following inequality holds:

Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğ´) > Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğµ).

(3)

Note that it is challenging to compute the probabilities Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğ´) and Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğµ) exactly because ğ‘“ is highly nonlinear in practice. To address the challenge, we first derive a lower bound of Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğ´) and an upper bound of Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğµ). Then, we require that the lower bound of Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğ´) is larger than the upper bound of Pr(ğ‘“ (ğ‘Œ ) = ğ‘ğµ). Specifically, we derive the lower bound and upper bound by constructing certain regions in the graph structure space {0, 1}ğ‘› such that the probabilities ğ‘Œ is in these regions can be efficiently computed for any ||ğ›¿ ||0 = ğ‘˜. Then, we iteratively search the maximum ğ‘˜ under the condition that the
lower bound is larger than the upper bound. Finally, we treat the
maximum ğ‘˜ as the certified perturbation size ğ¾.

