We have several observations on our major theorems. â€¢ Our theorems are applicable to any base node/graph classifier. Moreover, although we focus on classifiers on graphs, our theorems are applicable to any base classifier that takes binary features as input. â€¢ Our certified perturbation size ğ¾ depends on ğ‘ğ´, ğ‘ğµ, and ğ›½. In particular, when the probability bounds ğ‘ğ´ and ğ‘ğµ are tighter, our certified perturbation size ğ¾ is larger. We use the probability bounds ğ‘ğ´ and ğ‘ğµ instead of their exact values, because it is challenging to compute ğ‘ğ´ and ğ‘ğµ exactly. â€¢ When no assumptions on the base classifier are made and randomized smoothing with the noise distribution defined in Equation 1 is used, it is impossible to certify a perturbation size larger than ğ¾.

3.3 Certification in Practice

Computing our certified perturbation size ğ¾ in practice faces two

challenges. The first challenge is to estimate the probability bounds

ğ‘ğ´ and ğ‘ğµ. The second challenge is to solve the optimization prob-

lem in Equation 11 to get ğ¾ with the given ğ‘ğ´ and ğ‘ğµ. We leverage the method developed in [21] to address the first challenge, and we

develop an efficient algorithm to address the second challenge.

